The article reflects on the tragic shooting that took place in El Paso three years ago, where 23 people lost their lives and 22 others were injured. The writer emphasizes the importance of remembering the lives lost and acknowledging the courage and resilience of the survivors and their loved ones. The article also highlights the progress made in addressing both hate and gun violence, including executive actions and bipartisan legislation. The writer mentions signing bipartisan legislation to improve hate crimes reporting and enhance training for law enforcement. They also mention the need for the Senate to act on a bill recently passed by the House that would ban weapons used in such shootings. The writer concludes by stating their commitment to making communities safer and the responsibility owed to the families and communities affected by tragedies like the one in El Paso.